film star Scarlett Johansson has tried and failed to get a legal ban</a> on its English translation.</p> <p>The story, translated by Anthea Bell, concerns Arthur, a handsome yet modest young car mechanic with no girlfriend and an awful tragedy in his family background. One morning he opens his front door and the first thing he sees is – <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/scarlettjohansson\" title=\"\">Scarlett Johansson</a>! Her luscious husky-voiced sexiness is unmistakable, though she seems tired and troubled, with a weird tale to tell about just having come from the Dinard film festival.</p> <p>She wants to hang out with Arthur, apparently charmed by a glimpse she had of him being nice to a sweet little girl. Dazzled though he is by this glorious situation, Arthur senses something is amiss, because – and here is the whole ostensible point of the novel and the reason why Johansson’s legal action largely failed – it turns out to not be Johansson at all. She is a young woman called Jeanine Foucamprez who has been imprisoned by fate in a face and body that looks exactly like Johansson’s. If this sounds enviable, it isn’t. Though desirable, Foucamprez is desired by men who can’t get over her Scarlett-ness; she has no desire to be a professional look-alike and no identity of her own. The only identity available to her is that of Johansson, and that is already taken. As their relationship develops (he looks a bit like <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/ryan-gosling\" title=\"\">Ryan Gosling</a>, incidentally), Foucamprez hopes that real love will free her from this 21st-century identity crisis.</p> <p>The author all too clearly had his eye on a juicy movie deal for this high-concept romp – he even has a romcom-type “montage” of happy memories just before the end – and I suspect he hoped that Johansson would be a good sport and play Foucamprez herself. A film version is, after all, effectively impossible without her. Presumably the actor suspected this as well, and it contributed to her intense irritation at the way the author was presuming to make free with her identity, reputation and prestige as some kind of jokey avatar.</p> <p>Movie stars from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/charliechaplin\" title=\"\">Chaplin</a> to Dietrich have been dragooned into literary cameos before. And this would have been a neat idea for an ironic short story, with its gruesome touches and final Ballardian flourish. But Delacourt wants us to sign up for a romantic novel, and he will keep trying to have his cake and eat it by making lots of pop-culture movie references, sprinkling a little postmodern stardust on his prose while inviting readers to smile knowingly at the absurdity of Hollywood celebrity culture and establishing his literary bona fides with incessant highbrow references to the poet <a href=\"http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/jean-follain\" title=\"\">Jean Follain</a>.</p> <p>Weirdly, despite the blizzard of filmic namechecks, Delacourt doesn’t mention the specific films that must have influenced him: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/notting-hill\" title=\"\"><em>Notting Hill</em></a>, in which <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/juliaroberts\" title=\"\">Julia Roberts</a>’s movie star falls for humble bookshop owner <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/hugh-grant\" title=\"\">Hugh Grant</a> (incidentally, there’s a gag in <em>Ocean’s Twelve</em> about Roberts’s character passing herself off as Julia Roberts) and Jonathan Glazer’s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/mar/15/scarlett-johansson-under-skin-extraterrestrial\" title=\"\"><em>Under The Skin</em></a>, with Johansson playing an alien in Glasgow, in which the star filmed sequences with unwitting members of the public.</p> <p>By accident or design, Delacourt invokes interesting ideas, such as the loneliness involved in having beauty or celebrity, as well as the torment of those without them. “You don’t understand the misfortune of ugly women who know themselves to be beautiful,” says Foucamprez. But genuinely beautiful women and men have a refined misfortune of their own. They experience the same kind of power accorded to the well-known; people find themselves liking them without quite knowing why, and their views are listened to with unmerited respect. (A male celebrity once told me that his growing fame made him feel like a woman who was getting increasingly younger and more beautiful.) Yet the surfaces of celebrity and physical beauty are of limited interest: they are the first thing this novel wants to see – and the only thing. The book doesn’t offer us anything much, other than a brush with ersatz fame.</p> <p>• To order<strong> </strong><em>The First Thing You See</em><strong> </strong>for £10.39 go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/285464/?utm_source=editoriallink  &amp;utm_medium=\" merch&amp;utm_campaign=\"article&quot;&quot;\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"The English translation of this high-concept Hollywood romp, featuring a character that appears to be the film star, is a supercilious meditation on celebrity","headline":"The First Thing You See by Grégoire Delacourt review – the novel Scarlett Johansson tried to ban","byline":"Peter Bradshaw","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2015/9/4/1441377396150/Under-the-Skin---2014-001.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-10-23T15:34:00+01:00","standfirst":"<p>The English translation of this high-concept Hollywood romp, featuring a character that appears to be the film star, is a supercilious meditation on celebrity</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/sep/09/the-first-thing-you-see-gregoire-delacourt-scarlett-johansson","apiUrl":"http://content.guardia