n.com/books/2012/aug/10/toby-room-pat-barker-review\"><em>Toby’s Room</em></a>. We’ve seen Paul fighting in the trenches and have watched Elinor grieving for her brother’s death in the first world war – a grief that resurfaces now as she faces loss once again.</p> <p>Celebrating the destruction of his home, Paul is also a familiar figure for anyone acquainted with the wartime escapades of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/grahamgreene\">Graham Greene</a>, who expressed almost identical sentiments when his Clapham house was destroyed at a similar stage of the blitz. The parallels do not end there. Paul works as an ARP warden in exactly the same location as Greene, while Paul’s lover Sandra resembles Greene’s lover Dorothy in shape, age and temperament. Sandra shares Dorothy’s ability to down pints unusually speedily, and Paul and Sandra begin their affair, as Greene and Dorothy did, when they find themselves leaning out of opposite windows.</p> <p>Paul is not the only character to be modelled on a wartime writer in a novel that attempts to achieve authenticity by including actual experiences of the blitz. Elinor’s life owes something to that of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/elizabeth-bowen\">Elizabeth Bowen</a> and much more to that of Rose Macaulay, with Elinor even using <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/virginiawoolf\">Virginia Woolf</a>’s portrayal of Macaulay as a “spindle-shanked withered virgin” as a description of herself. There is a scene depicting Elinor’s night on duty as an ambulance driver that exactly replicates one of Macaulay’s shifts. The smells, sounds and sights are the same, as are the interjections of the rescue workers and of the people trapped in the ruins.</p> <p>This is an interesting way to construct a historical novel. Readers may find that the documentary detail provides a reassuring accuracy of time and place; for me it sometimes made the characterisation rather flimsy. When Greene celebrated the bombing of his house he was welcoming the end of an already weary marriage and exhibiting a life-long enthusiasm for destruction. This was a man who had played Russian roulette with a loaded gun as a child, and repeatedly sought out danger in war zones, requiring the proximity to death to feel fully alive. Paul has exhibited none of these characteristics in previous novels, so his relief when his home is destroyed is as mystifying to the reader as it is to his wife.</p> <p>Readers in search of an evocative second world war novel might be better advised to return to the strange intensity of Bowen’s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jan/12/100-best-novels-elizabeth-bowen-heat-of-the-day-blitz\"><em>The Heat of the Day</em></a> or the lyrical sensuality of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/sep/24/classics.sebastianfaulks\">Henry Green</a>’s <em>Caught.</em> There are flashes of originality in Barker’s descriptions of the upstairs window of a burning house “wide open in the heat as if the house were gasping for breath” or of wartime London as “a settlement on a river, lit by guttering candles after dark”. More frequently, however, the novel becomes saturated by its historical detail.</p> <p>Although written in insistently colloquial, free indirect discourse, the stream of consciousness and even the diary entries of the characters frequently include documentary observations that no one would actually make to themselves. One character is attracted to the sound of a prostitute walking in the blackout “because they hammered tacks into the heels and toes, to make them stand out”. Elinor observes in her diary that the good thing about taking on work as a war artist is that “it’ll give me access to materials, and that’s no small thing, these days, because they’re getting awfully expensive”. And Barker’s plot is as strained as her descriptions, relying on a series of unlikely coincidences.</p> <p>As an art student in <em>Life Class</em>, Paul was informed by his tutor that “most people who come here are bursting with something they want to say” but that it was strangely unclear what Paul hoped to say through his paintings. Reading <em>Noonday</em>, I wondered if the same had become true for Barker. However, if this novel does have something to say then it is not about the blitz but about the rewards and complexity of middle-aged love.</p> <p>“Why should falling in love be reserved for the very young?” Bowen asked during the war. Barker’s novel might also lead us to ask why falling in love should be reserved for new lovers. It is moving watching Paul and Elinor losing and then refinding each other, slow and uncertain as they attempt to discover what is left of a marriage once its setting has been destroyed. This is love expressed not through clock-stopped sex but through the quiet warming of a tin of soup, through familiar bodies lying tentatively “side by side, not speaking, not even looking at each other, while the long hours of darkness passed”.</p> <p>• Lara Feigel is the author of <em>The Love-charm of Bombs: Restless Lives in the Second World War. </em>To order a copy for £15.19, go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/315633/?utm_source=editoriallink &amp;utm_medium=\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min. p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"The final instalment of Barker’s war trilogy draws on actual experiences of the blitz, but its real strength lies in the way it captures the complexities of love","headline":"Noonday by Pat Barker review – love and loss in the second world war","byline":"Lara Feigel","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2015/9/4/1441383447285/Pat-Barker-001.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-10-23T17:13:00+01:00","standfirst":"<p>The final instalment of Barker’s war trilogy draws on actual experiences of the blitz, but its real strength lies in the way it captures the complexities of love</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/sep/09/noonday-pat-barker-review-love-lost-second-world-war","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2015/sep/09/noonday-pat-barker-review-love-lost-second-world-war","sectionName":"Books","tags":[{"id":"books/series/book-of-the-day","webTitle":"Book of the day","type":"series","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/book-of-the-day","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/book-of-the-day","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/fiction","webTitle":"Fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"tone/reviews","webTitle":"Reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/reviews","references":[]},{"id":"books/pat-barker","webTitle":"Pat Barker","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/pat-barker","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/pat-barker","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/lara-feigel","webTitle":"Lara Feigel","r2ContributorId":"53878"