06-460x276.jpeg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718628382/f23668a2-3123-40d5-9f79-7c4bec5c3706-460x276.jpeg","source":"PR","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Kate Everson","height":"276","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"632e7b95f7109ca72271329b07006ca78c87bf33","width":"460"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718628576/b7e1ad14-f2a9-41e3-a546-5679c838535a-140x84.jpeg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718628576/b7e1ad14-f2a9-41e3-a546-5679c838535a-140x84.jpeg","source":"PR","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Kate Everson","height":"84","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"632e7b95f7109ca72271329b07006ca78c87bf33","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718628911/d037a2b7-9ab5-41c3-a5a2-77d95eb5213d-300x180.jpeg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718628911/d037a2b7-9ab5-41c3-a5a2-77d95eb5213d-300x180.jpeg","source":"PR","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Kate Everson","height":"180","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"632e7b95f7109ca72271329b07006ca78c87bf33","width":"300"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718629158/facde9c8-5046-46f1-899e-beab2970c886-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718629158/facde9c8-5046-46f1-899e-beab2970c886-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg","source":"PR","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Kate Everson","height":"279","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"632e7b95f7109ca72271329b07006ca78c87bf33","width":"465"}},{"type":"image","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718629763/690ff513-2223-4ffe-9e9d-b38508f32091-380x228.jpeg","typeData":{"displayCredit":"true","secureFile":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718629763/690ff513-2223-4ffe-9e9d-b38508f32091-380x228.jpeg","source":"PR","imageType":"Photograph","altText":"Kate Everson","height":"228","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"632e7b95f7109ca72271329b07006ca78c87bf33","width":"380"}}]}],"rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Why I've written a book for teenagers about taking drugs","references":[],"webPublicationDate":"2015-09-08T18:00:04Z","fields":{"wordcount":"1269","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4c7ge","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>I’ve written a book about drugs. Sorry, Mum.<br /></p> <p>Right, now that’s out of the way, let’s move on to why I wrote it.<br /></p> <p>I was searching for the “real me” for a long time. When I was six years old, a teacher kept me in after school for not doing enough work. She shouted at me: furious, relentless, vein-popping, until my mum arrived. Other parents had alerted her and she rushed into the classroom. Vaguely I recall the dusty, rubbery air and the parquet flooring, but mainly I picture the teacher’s towering height (I was short for my age which can’t have helped) and I feel again the FEAR; my whole body, super-charged, shaking, the gallop of my heartbeat in my ears, my evaporating stomach, and the voice saying, “you’re not good enough.” That voice would eventually become my own, because, as far as I can remember, that was the moment that my angst-ridden, insomniac journey with depression and anxiety began. Only I didn’t know it yet.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/jan/01/top-10-teen-books-to-save-your-life-jennifer-niven\">Jennifer Niven's top 10 teen books to save your life</a> </p> </aside>  <p>When I was seven years old at a new school, I cried all day, every day. When I was 14 years old, I cried in maths lessons. An improvement, I guess. It wasn’t that I was bad at maths; I knew my way around a quadratic equation, let me tell you. It was that I was bad at being at school. For me, the environment totally sucked because A) there were all these people who were obviously smarter/cooler/better than me; and B) every time I did or said anything, the voice was saying, “Stop that immediately! You’re not good enough! You’re a disgrace!”<br /></p> <p>Obviously, this is not a great way to be. So I tried to fix it. Which is hard, when you don’t understand the problem. I just wanted to feel better, to be happy. Maybe I could displace the feelings of inadequacy somehow? How about smoking? Or booze? Let’s try that… You see where this is going…<br /></p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/jan/21/teenager-feminism-louise-o-neill-only-ever-yours\">Louise O'Neill: my journey to feminism</a> </p> </aside>  <p><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a> is not the first book about teenage addiction; <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/junk.html\">Junk</a> by Melvin Burgess is the seminal YA novel about heroin addiction, there are multiple US books about meth: <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/crank.html\">Crank</a> by Ellen Hopkins, <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/tweak.html\">Tweak </a>by Nic Sheff are examples. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/go-ask-alice.html\">Go Ask Alice</a>, presented as the authentic diary of a troubled teen’s drug experience, later controversially exposed as a work of fiction, is a classic. Written in 1971, its message is still relevant, but nearly 45 years on, today’s teens risk finding the style outdated.<br /></p> <p>When it comes to drugs in fiction, we’re presented with extremes – heroin, meth and their sometimes horrific consequences are well documented. As much as we need these stories, what about the countless teens using party drugs? In hindsight it’s easy to say I was aiming to tell a story that’s relevant to them, but if that were the case, it was an unconscious doing. I just wanted to tell an honest story: highs, lows, warts and all. I wanted to write about a teen’s descent into drug use and it was natural to draw on first-hand experience of an overwhelming need to fix myself by any means.<br /></p> <p>In <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a>, Carla is desperate to belong, to be <em>someone</em>. But where do you draw the line? When do you become <em>someone</em>? Imagine: in the distance you see a tower. When you reach that tower, you believe you’ll be perfect. You eventually arrive, battered and bruised from the epic journey, and climb to the top to look out. Guess what? Ahead is another tower, one that was unobservable from your original starting point, so you pack up, and set out again on your quest for perfection. Guys, there is always another tower. Carla thinks being popular will solve all her problems. She’s so committed to changing herself, to reaching the next tower, that she refuses to acknowledge the damage it’s doing. Pressure, whether from peers or that you put upon yourself, is a fearsome motivator.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/aug/28/banned-burned-or-simply-life-changing-what-are-the-best-dangerous-books\">Banned, burned, or simply life changing: what are the best dangerous books?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Like me, Carla is shy, self-questioning – searching for that elusive, optimal version of herself, the princess atop the tower. But I know something she doesn’t: the “real me” is a phantom. It was only whilst editing <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a>, over 20 years after the “you’re not good enough” voice began whispering in my ear, that I realised I had a problem, and decided to get help. Twenty years! It’s not at all easy to break the habits of a lifetime – to challenge the FEAR, and quiet the voice – but instead of filling my face with booze or whatever, and with a lot of support, I’ve started to accept that A) I’ve done a pretty good job of life so far; and B) what other people think doesn’t really matter. Screw the tower. I’m going to have a nice little picnic down here on the grass with my friends and family, because they don’t care a jot whether I’m up there.</p> <p>Happiness rarely just happens. Mostly you make some choices and you\u001F\u001F\u001F\u001F work at it. You tell yourself that you <em>are</em> good enough. It’s hard at first, but eventually, you start to believe it. I was lost, looking for the real me just like Carla. And what I found was that I’m alright just the way I am. It’s a difficult lesson that perhaps I wish I’d learned sooner, but then, without angst as my companion all this time I never would have written <em>Drop</em>. Our flaws make us human and our stories real. (On that note: to the teacher from all those years ago – don’t sweat it. You had your faults and I have mine. I’m as much genes as experience, and in a way you helped me become who I am. What I’m trying to say is ... we’re cool. And you know what? I’m doing OK now.)<br /></p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>It’s a fact that some teens do drugs. They’re not necessarily bad people; they’re regular people, led by experience to choose a certain path. In <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a>, Carla, by her own admission, is a normal sort of girl, a bit shy, a bit sad… As I said, a lot like me. It was very important to me that she be ordinary. Or at least perceive herself as ordinary. <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a> could be anyone’s story, even younger teens’. It’s no wonder. Fierce expectations from educators; the massive mental and physical upheaval of being an adolescent; peer pressure, or simple curiosity can make drugs a tempting prospect. And let’s not forget, some drugs do make people feel good. You don’t have to come from a broken home or have a skeleton in your closet to feel drawn to take drugs. Sometimes it’s a just a simple quest to feel good.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"9dd8bf31a0ec2f33e03febae4ec2fb075712ed16\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441715912469/da238823-c929-4d7d-8ec7-3dfd569e57d9-274x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Drop\" width=\"274\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"> </span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>It’s hard growing up. Exams, break-ups, betrayals and bad decisions inevitably mark the road to adulthood. There’s no map to help navigate this journey, but there are books, lots of them. Read <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a> if you like, or any of the others<em>.</em> While media scare-mongering and demonisation of drug users continues, it isn’t always easy for young people to access adequate and unbiased information. Fear of judgement can force the vulnerable into the shadows, where it’s harder to spot them. Honest stories can inform, advise and reassure. I hope that <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a> will be one of these.</p> <ul> <li><strong>Katie Everson’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a> is available at the Guardian bookshop. More advice for young people on <a href=\"http://www.thesite.org/\">TheSite.org</a></strong><br /></li> </ul>","productionOffice":"UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"Being told ‘you’re not good enough’ at school – and the following descent into depression and drug use in an attempt to fix herself – is the background to Katie Everson’s book Drop","headline":"Why I've written a book for teenagers about taking drugs","byline":"Katie Everson","commentable":"false","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/9/8/1441718628576/b7e1ad14-f2a9-41e3-a546-5679c838535a-140x84.jpeg","commentCloseDate":"2015-09-08T18:00:04Z","standfirst":"<p>Being told ‘you’re not good enough’ at school – and the following descent into depression and drug use in an attempt to fix herself – is the background to Katie Everson’s book <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/318573/\">Drop</a></p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/sep/08/teenage-drugs-books-katie-everson","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2015/sep/08/teenage-drugs-books-katie-everson","sectionName":"Children's books","tags":[{"id":"childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Children's books","type":"blog","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id"