ime, it’s going to be such an incredible destination and event that they’re going to be really psyched up for getting there,” Kelly said. “I’m not saying I’m not psyched up for the rest of this. But in some ways, almost being halfway through, a lot of what we’re going to be doing is very similar to what we’ve already done.”</p> <p>A Mars crew also won’t have people coming and going, as is currently the case at the space station.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"3dc1b0e36e6c08143b21049a7c299c37026958d5\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3dc1b0e36e6c08143b21049a7c299c37026958d5/0_0_4096_2459/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A screen of the Russian Mission Control Center shows live television of the International Space Station crew members as they take part in the news conference on Tuesday.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A screen of the Russian mission control centre shows live television of the International Space Station crew members during a news conference on Tuesday.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Maxim Shipenkov/EPA</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Nine men from four countries are on board the orbiting lab until Friday, when three of them – representing Russia, Kazakhstan and Denmark – will return to Earth.</p> <p>Kelly and Russian Mikhail Kornienko will remain there until next March. For Nasa, it will represent the longest space mission ever. Nasa officials consider the year-long mission a necessary step as the agency looks ahead to even longer Mars expeditions sometime in the 2030s.</p> <p>With its sights set on the red planet, Nasa is embracing The Martian – and vice versa.</p> <p>Like Kelly, Damon recently signed up to have his name sent to Mars aboard Nasa’s next lander, named InSight. The spacecraft is due to launch next March and arrive at Mars next September. Posing with his “boarding pass” to the red planet, Kelly noted in a tweet over the weekend that in the time he has already spent in orbit, he would be almost to Mars. He and Kornienko took off from Kazakhstan in March.</p> <p>Nasa’s “boarding passes” to Mars, via the InSight lander, were available online until 11.59pm ET on Tuesday. As of noon, the sign-up sheet exceeded 765,000.</p>","productionOffice":"US","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"US crew are on board International Space Station as part of a year-long mission seen as vital preparation for a future mission to the red planet","headline":"Nasa astronauts have read The Martian and hope to see the movie in space","byline":"Associated Press in Cape Canaveral, Florida","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/8bea1b6b64ca199ec536a24df60653e9c31669f8/0_138_5120_3075/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-09-11T13:45:00-04:00","standfirst":"<p>US crew are on board International Space Station as part of a year-long mission seen as vital preparation for a future mission to the red planet</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/sep/08/nasa-astronauts-the-martian-book-movie-space","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/science/2015/sep/08/nasa-astronauts-the-martian-book-movie-space","sectionName":"Science","tags":[{"id":"science/nasa","webTitle":"Nasa","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/science/nasa","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/science/nasa","sectionName":"Science","references":[]},{"id":"science/space","webTitle":"Space","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/science/space","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/science/space","sectionName":"Science","references":[]},{"id":"science/science","webTitle":"Science","type":"keyword","sectionId":"science","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/science/science","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/science/science","sectionName":"Science","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId